default&#xa0;defaultNote on Table 5default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultEndnote:defaultData on recalls is reported separately to prisoner population by length of sentence data. It was therefore necessary, in some instances, to estimate the number of recalls to arrive at the total number of prisoners who would be enfranchised and able to vote under each option, as many recalled prisoners would be serving sentences below the thresholds set by the options. The process for doing this is as follows.
defaultThe recall population was estimated for each sentence length band based on the size of each sentence length band relative to the prison population liable to be recalled. The number of those recalled to sentences of less than 4 years is estimated to be 1,800 prisoners. – This number was not added to the population figures for the sentence length as it is an estimate only, but should be considered as part of this population. 
defaultNo recalls were estimated for the total population of prisoners serving sentences of 6 months and less in England and Wales. These prisoners are eligible for release on Home Detention Curfew (HDC) licence before their automatic release date (and could be recalled from that) but they are not currently subject to any licence or recall during the second half of their sentence. Therefore, recalls from HDC represent only a very small proportion in the total population of recalls.
default In Scotland, prisoners serving sentences of less than 4 years are in most cases not eligible for release on license – no recalls were therefore apportioned.
