defaultSchedule 4 to the Representation of the People Act 2000 makes provision with respect to the manner of voting at elections, in particular absent voting in parliamentary and local government elections in England, Wales and Scotland (see section 12 RPA 2000).  Paragraph 2 of Schedule 4 provides:
defaultManner of voting at parliamentary or local government electionsdefault2default(1) This paragraph applies to determine the manner of voting of a person entitled to vote as an elector at a parliamentary or local government election.
default(2) He may vote in person at the polling station allotted to him under the appropriate rules, unless he is entitled as an elector to an absent vote at the election.
default(3) He may vote by post if he is entitled as an elector to vote by post at the election.
default(4) If he is entitled to vote by proxy at the election, he may so vote unless, before a ballot paper has been issued for him to vote by proxy, he applies at the polling station allotted to him under the appropriate rules for a ballot paper for the purpose of voting in person, in which case he may vote in person there.
default…
default(6) Nothing in the preceding provisions of this paragraph applies to—
default(a) . . .
default(b) 
defaulta
default person to whom section 7A of that Act (persons remanded in custody) applies,
defaultwhether he is registered by virtue of that provision or not; and such a person may only vote by post or by proxy (where he is entitled as an elector to vote by post or, as the case may be, by proxy at the election)
default.
default[(6A) Sub-paragraph (2) above does not prevent a person, at the polling station allotted to him, marking a tendered ballot paper in pursuance of rule 40(1ZC) or (1ZE) of the parliamentary elections rules.]
default[(6B) Sub-paragraph (2) above does not prevent a person, at the polling station allotted to him at a local government election in Scotland, marking a tendered ballot paper in pursuance of any provision—
default(a) 
defaultmade
